      <profileDesc>
         <creation notBefore="0500">The long investigation carried out after the dis-covery and publication of the Syriac version of the T.D. 
            has concluded  (cp. <bibl><ptr target="bm:Coquin1974TestDom"/></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="bm:Ellwardt2005TestDom"/></bibl>) that the work, one of the last products of the pseudo-apostolic literature, was originally composed in Greek in the 5th cent. (contra, cp. Drijvers 1994). 
            The almost totally lost <ref target="#t4greek">Greek original</ref> is attested by three integral versions in <ref target="#t3syriac">Syriac</ref>, <ref target="#t2arabic">Arabic</ref>, and Geez, plus a few Latin and Georgian fragments, and the widely attested Coptic version of the Mystagogy.  See <bibl><ptr target="bm:Bausi2010TestDom"/></bibl>.
         </creation>
